WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:01.320
Context.

00:03.600 --> 00:06.800
Context is a, I teach this intentionally pretty late

00:06.800 --> 00:08.400
in the course, or in terms of like late

00:08.400 --> 00:10.640
of the fundamentals of React.

00:11.960 --> 00:14.960
It's a powerful tool,

00:14.960 --> 00:17.760
and I see new React developers get tempted

00:17.760 --> 00:18.840
to use it all over the place

00:18.840 --> 00:22.160
because it simplifies the writing part of React,

00:22.160 --> 00:23.840
and I will say it greatly complicates

00:23.840 --> 00:25.600
the maintenance part of React.

00:26.600 --> 00:28.920
This is another way of me saying, me begging you,

00:29.000 --> 00:30.400
as your perhaps future coworkers,

00:30.400 --> 00:33.720
you'd be very sparing with your use of context.

00:33.720 --> 00:35.720
Use it, you know, with great power

00:35.720 --> 00:37.040
comes great responsibility.

00:37.040 --> 00:39.440
You know, that's, I think I'm the first person

00:39.440 --> 00:40.320
to ever say that.

00:44.160 --> 00:46.800
No, it's just, props come from parent to child,

00:46.800 --> 00:49.400
parent to child, and it becomes very explicit,

00:49.400 --> 00:51.080
the data flow of your app.

00:51.080 --> 00:54.040
Context is like being able to dump data into a portal,

00:54.040 --> 00:56.880
and then somewhere else being able to receive data

00:56.880 --> 00:58.120
out of the portal.

00:58.120 --> 01:01.240
And so if you have, you know, five components

01:01.240 --> 01:03.240
that are passing data from parent to child,

01:03.240 --> 01:05.720
parent to child, it can get a little annoying.

01:05.720 --> 01:09.280
That problem's called the prop drilling problem.

01:11.400 --> 01:14.200
It's tempting to use context there, right?

01:16.440 --> 01:21.120
I'm gonna say, unless you're using that context

01:21.120 --> 01:25.360
in multiple places, that state in multiple different places,

01:25.360 --> 01:27.360
just deal with the prop drilling.

01:27.400 --> 01:29.440
I know it's annoying, but it is helpful.

01:30.680 --> 01:32.960
But there are some things that are legitimately

01:32.960 --> 01:35.440
what I would call app level state.

01:35.440 --> 01:37.560
A really good example of this would be like a user, right?

01:37.560 --> 01:39.720
So if someone logs into your website,

01:40.560 --> 01:42.800
that doesn't just affect one part of your website,

01:42.800 --> 01:45.320
it affects everything in your website, right?

01:45.320 --> 01:47.640
You're showing the user their information,

01:47.640 --> 01:49.520
their checkout information, their address, right?

01:49.520 --> 01:51.800
And that's all pulling from the same piece

01:51.800 --> 01:53.560
of user information.

01:53.560 --> 01:58.480
So you could have like app.jsx have you state user, right?

01:58.480 --> 02:00.400
And then pass that into everything.

02:01.560 --> 02:03.800
That doesn't seem like a good idea to me, right?

02:03.800 --> 02:05.760
I think it's better to say like, hey,

02:05.760 --> 02:09.000
we have this app level state that is the user,

02:09.000 --> 02:12.560
and then anyone can pull out of the context who the user is.

02:13.640 --> 02:15.440
Does that make sense?

02:15.440 --> 02:17.960
So you're looking for what I call app level state

02:17.960 --> 02:22.000
as opposed to like view level state or like localized state.

02:22.000 --> 02:24.760
That's where context is useful.

02:24.760 --> 02:28.120
Theme is another one that will sometimes come up, right?

02:28.120 --> 02:29.520
If someone switches their theme,

02:29.520 --> 02:32.040
that affects not just one piece of your code,

02:32.040 --> 02:34.360
it affects a lot of the pieces of your code.

02:34.360 --> 02:37.280
So you might use theme as another piece of context.

02:39.960 --> 02:43.200
A lot of time libraries, so like react router

02:43.200 --> 02:44.840
or 10 stack router, which we're gonna look at here

02:44.840 --> 02:47.720
in a little bit, those will use context quite a bit.

02:47.720 --> 02:48.900
It's also made for those things,

02:48.900 --> 02:50.040
and you don't have to care about those things

02:50.040 --> 02:52.640
because that's their problem, not yours.

02:52.640 --> 02:57.640
So in our app here, we have a header,

02:57.800 --> 03:01.400
and I wanna put like a little like indicator there

03:01.400 --> 03:02.560
of what's in your cart.

03:03.480 --> 03:06.360
And then the other thing that you can say about cart

03:06.360 --> 03:08.920
being as a function of context is like,

03:08.920 --> 03:12.840
if someone navigates away from this order page,

03:12.840 --> 03:15.240
so let's say there was an about page or a contact page,

03:15.240 --> 03:17.160
which we'll build here in just a second.

03:18.080 --> 03:19.600
If they navigate it to the contact page

03:19.600 --> 03:21.780
and then they navigated back to the order page,

03:21.780 --> 03:23.280
what would happen to the cart?

03:26.520 --> 03:28.120
Disappear, right?

03:28.120 --> 03:29.680
Why?

03:29.680 --> 03:34.680
If this gets unmounted, all of its state goes away, right?

03:34.720 --> 03:36.960
It doesn't get saved if it gets removed from the DOM, right?

03:36.960 --> 03:40.320
So if I come over here to app.jsx,

03:40.320 --> 03:41.520
you know what, we can literally do this.

03:41.520 --> 03:43.520
We're gonna add a bunch of stuff right here.

03:44.720 --> 03:47.460
I'm just gonna remove this, okay?

03:47.460 --> 03:49.240
So I just removed it from the DOM,

03:49.880 --> 03:52.200
which would be the same thing from unrendering it, right?

03:52.200 --> 03:53.760
And then I'm gonna add it back.

03:54.840 --> 03:56.200
Notice that the cart is empty again, right?

03:56.200 --> 03:58.840
Because it got totally thrown away.

03:58.840 --> 04:00.080
It would be the same thing if you routed

04:00.080 --> 04:02.840
to a different page and came back.

04:02.840 --> 04:06.240
Now again, we are in the business of making pizza money,

04:06.240 --> 04:07.840
right?

04:07.840 --> 04:10.600
So we wanna keep that cart full, right?

04:10.600 --> 04:12.760
Always be keeping cart fulls.

